    </div>
  </div>
    <div class="elementListBrownSeparator"></div>



  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1596894898" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1596894898" />
    <a title="Stacey D. " class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5063553-stacey-d"><img alt="Stacey D. " src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1599406138p2/5063553.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1596894898?book_show_action=true">Nov 09, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Stacey D. " class="user" itemprop="url" name="Stacey D. " href="/user/show/5063553-stacey-d">Stacey D. </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5063553-stacey-d?shelf=1001-books-before-you-die">1001-books-before-you-die</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1596894898" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1790649931656734827">Truth. I became interested in reading this book after seeing the extremely creepy, but so well done movie, <i>Cape Fear,</i> years ago, when the young daughter of this Southern family (and story narrator), Danielle, is assigned to read it for school. I wondered what it was about Look Homeward, Angel that was integral to the story and to Danielle&apos;s character. I think I get it now.<br/><br/>Wolfe&apos;s most famous novel is set in the bucolic, but deeply prejudiced South of 100 years ago. The Great War breaks out in 19</span>
  <span id="freeText1790649931656734827" style="display:none">Truth. I became interested in reading this book after seeing the extremely creepy, but so well done movie, <i>Cape Fear,</i> years ago, when the young daughter of this Southern family (and story narrator), Danielle, is assigned to read it for school. I wondered what it was about Look Homeward, Angel that was integral to the story and to Danielle's character. I think I get it now.<br /><br />Wolfe's most famous novel is set in the bucolic, but deeply prejudiced South of 100 years ago. The Great War breaks out in 1914, cities and towns are expanding, motor cars appear. It's a coming of age story about Eugene Gant, the youngest of six children in the beleagured, dysfunctional Gant family. The book opens on W.O. Gant, the sad, alcoholic father who comes to Altamont, Catawba (a fictional town based on Wolfe's hometown of Asheville, NC) to start up a cemetery monument business. The angel of the title is one of his finest creations.<br /><br />From there, the third person narration describes selfish Gant, his courtship and marriage to the selfish and miserly Eliza who accumulates some wealth through her obsession with real estate deals, and their neglected, downtrodden children. Eliza runs a boarding house for wayward transients, prostitutes, etc., called Dixieland, which sucks up all her time and causes angry resentment in her husband and children. It's pretty clear early on that some of these kids are headed for shiftless adulthood, inheriting their father's love of the bottle and no set goals for the future. Eugene is the best of the lot: funny, intellectual, yet, eccentric and a loner. He escapes the sadness and constant angry tirades at home by attending an advanced school run by a lovely couple who encourage his education and set off his imagination. At 16, his stingy father sends him to the University of NC, where he is way too young for his freshman class. Gene struggles to fit in there and at home (which he hates), find acceptance for who he is and ultimately, find his place in the world.<br /><br />The story is somewhat gripping, about the South and our history and distant past as a nation, but I got tired of reading the angst-ridden fights that appear frequently throughout the novel. These people are trapped in a terrible, continuous cycle of screaming-i-hate-you-let's-forget-about-it-ness, before psychology and self-awareness take their place in society. No one apologizes; no one turns a new leaf. Except when someone dies, nothing changes for these people who are trapped in their own hell.<br /><br />As for the writing, the novel was hailed as modern and experimental in its day; it's also rawly autobiographical in scope - something altogether new to literature. To me, the language is really overwrought at the beginning of the book, but does improve a bit over time. Wolfe is a big fan of the 10-cent word, so have a dictionary nearby if you take on this doorstopper of a novel. As it's also very much about the ol' south, the n* word is used often, as are racial slurs and stereotypes about various minority groups, including Jews. Blech. There's also an interesting passage where the outcome of the Civil War on the South is discussed and one character comments, "Defeated, sir, but never beaten". And that attitude, I guess, lives in the hearts of many Southerners to this day.<br /><br />A funny note: I actually found the words bigly and dotage stated TWICE!! <br /><br />Finally, as a takeway from this novel, which I view as existentialist in its overall theme, I can't help but remember a quote taken from Livia Soprano in The Sopranos which I think is something both the Gants and Thomas Wolfe might agree with: <i>"In the end, you die in your own arms. It's all a big nothing."</i></span>
  <a data-text-id="1790649931656734827" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

