  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2884263132" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2884263132" />
    <a title="Carol Storm" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5032322-carol-storm"><img alt="Carol Storm" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442507712p2/5032322.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2884263132?book_show_action=true">Aug 14, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Carol Storm" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Carol Storm" href="/user/show/5032322-carol-storm">Carol Storm</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2884263132" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15611860960101558561">I hated so many things about this book -- the smug racism, the appalling sentimentality, the outrageous purple prose. At the same time, there were things that I admired -- the family is so dysfunctional, and cruel, and hateful, yet Wolfe captures how they care about each other and how they live together in a way that is incredibly fresh and modern and compelling. This book is almost 700 pages long, and I&apos;d say that about 200 pages are five-star quality, while 500 pages are one star or less. So I</span>
  <span id="freeText15611860960101558561" style="display:none">I hated so many things about this book -- the smug racism, the appalling sentimentality, the outrageous purple prose. At the same time, there were things that I admired -- the family is so dysfunctional, and cruel, and hateful, yet Wolfe captures how they care about each other and how they live together in a way that is incredibly fresh and modern and compelling. This book is almost 700 pages long, and I'd say that about 200 pages are five-star quality, while 500 pages are one star or less. So I'm giving the whole book two stars, which I think is generous. <br /><br />One thing that is fascinating about reading this book is that you can see all the influences on Wolfe, and also see how many writers he corrupted, I mean, influenced. The only problem is, he's almost always the weakest link in the chain -- Wolfe is worse than the people he learned from and the people he taught. Here's how I broke it down. <br /><br />THIS SIDE OF PARADISE by F. Scott Fitzgerald. This is a college novel that came out seven or eight years before Look Homeward Angel. It was F. Scott Fitzgerald's first novel, and it's pretty dated and ugly today. Lots of racism, snobbery, and anti-Semitic attitudes prevail. If you take all the very worst of early Fitzgerald and put it on steroids, that's what the college chapters in this book are like. Unless it's meant to be a parody of some sort. Check out this quote:<br /><br />"But Eugene was untroubled by any thought of a goal. He was mad with such ecstasy as he had never known. He was a centaur, moon-eyed and wild of mane, torn apart with hunger for the golden world. He became at times almost incapable of coherent speech. While talking with people, he would whinny suddenly into their startled faces, and leap away, his face contorted with an idiot joy. He would hurl himself squealing through the streets and along the paths, touched with the ecstasy of a thousand unspoken desires. The world lay before him for his picking – full of opulent cities, golden vintages, glorious triumphs, and lovely women, full of a thousand unmet and magnificent possibilities. Nothing was dull or tarnished. The strange enchanted coasts were unvisited. He was young and he could never die."<br /><br />If you think that's great writing, then this book is for you. But it wasn't for me!<br /><br />LONG DAY'S JOURNEY INTO NIGHT by Eugene O'Neill. This is O'Neill's greatest play, and it was written a good ten years after this book. But everything that's good here is echoed in O'Neill's play. The relationship between Eugene and his brother Ben is practically the only honest thing in this book, and the two of them are much like Edmund and Jamie. I loved when Eugene's mother told him he'd always be broke till he learned the value of a dollar. That's in O'Neill too! <br /><br />THE GRAPES OF WRATH by John Steinbeck. A lot of the fierce attacks on property in this book prefigure Steinbeck, and some of the family stuff too. There's one brief paragraph about the two brothers walking down the road together and it sounded just like Steinbeck writing about Tom and Al Joad. On the other hand, Steinbeck was a lot more restrained and focused than this guy. <br /><br />Now there's tons of racism in this book, and it offended me deeply. The black people in Eugene's home town all live in a slum called N-word town. And Wolfe writes out the N word with relish. Like he has to keep reminding you how much disdain he has for "those people." But the thing that bothered me wasn't just the racism. It was the smarmy way it's juxtaposed with the phony innocence, the phony idealism, the phony exuberance of Eugene Gant. <br /><br />We keep hearing Eugene say stuff like, "all the ancient civilizations were in him and he was destined to be greater than a 1000 pharaohs and rule a hundred tribes for a thousand years." (I kid you not, this is how Wolfe writes. So cool!) But like, he can groove on the Pharaohs but "those people" have to be kept in their place. He keeps talking about their "jungle wails" and "sounds of Africa" like they're not even human. And then he brags about teenage Eugene going down there at night and extorting sex from black women! I wasn't just mad enough to throw the book across the room -- my eyes were literally bugging out of my head. <br /><br />See, when you read Faulkner, he has all the wrong answers on the race question. But at least he knows it's an important question. He has a sense of the tragic failure of the South. But this moron has no sense of tragedy, no sense of reality, no sense of humor. (Except very rarely when you sense the whole thing is one big put on.) In the Sound and the Fury, Quentin Compson makes it clear he's not comfortable with blacks who don't know their place. That's why he hates Harvard so much. But Quentin Compson never pretends he's a happy person or that he can find a reason to live. His suicide and his racism are both symptoms of the same disease. But with Eugene Gant all you get is goofball sentimentality and infantile delusions of grandeur. He's innocent, a child of nature, and yet he's shaking down black women for sex while he's still a paper boy. But that doesn't mean he's a mean, petty little redneck. Oh no! He's destined to rule vast empires, make love to ten thousand Egyptian queens, build vast new cities on the dark side of the moon . . .<br /><br />I could go on and on, but what's the point? You have to read this book to believe it. But I guarantee you won't believe it!<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="15611860960101558561" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


