    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_251527624" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/251527624" />
    <a title="Mat" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7120830-mat"><img alt="Mat" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1585499177p2/7120830.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/251527624?book_show_action=true">Dec 26, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mat" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mat" href="/user/show/7120830-mat">Mat</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer251527624" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10167955415005540219">Look Homeward, Angel is possibly one of the most beautiful and touching books I have ever read and definitely ranks in my Top Ten favourite books of all time. Thomas Wolfe is a true master of imagery and description and this book deserves a place on any shelf of bonafide American literature classics. I don’t know why people find this a challenge to get through at all. I could not put it down and finished it in a week. <br/><br/>His style of writing IS rambling and Wolfe does go off on many tangents (or ‘d</span>
  <span id="freeText10167955415005540219" style="display:none">Look Homeward, Angel is possibly one of the most beautiful and touching books I have ever read and definitely ranks in my Top Ten favourite books of all time. Thomas Wolfe is a true master of imagery and description and this book deserves a place on any shelf of bonafide American literature classics. I don’t know why people find this a challenge to get through at all. I could not put it down and finished it in a week. <br /><br />His style of writing IS rambling and Wolfe does go off on many tangents (or ‘divagations’ as he would describe it and incidentally one of the many new words I learned from this book!) but he always brings the plot back on course. As some other reviewers have wisely pointed out, it may be hard for modern readers to enjoy such long, rambling novels these days, thanks in no small part to the advent of television. Over the past 50-60 years, humans have seen their attention spans become increasingly shorter and shorter. With the immense sea of information now available at our fingertrips in the age of the internet, we are constantly wanting information which is concise and engaging and perhaps even entertaining. Just like taking public transport or choosing a Calorie Mate for a meal, we have all become EFFICIENCY freaks, which means little time to plunk yourself down in a nice old leather armchair to read a thick tome of Thomas Wolfe. Therefore, I know many people, friends included, who would not have the patience to put up with reading 500+ page novels.<br /><br />People complain it doesn’t have plot. Plot, plot, plot – seems like that’s the only reason why some people read books these days. Whatever happened to the old pleasure of losing yourself in the beauty of the language (like reading Shakespeare) or a novel which really makes you think about life and people (take The Confidence Man by Melville for example)? <br /><br />Let me reassure you dear reader that the quality of the writing is absolutely top-notch – superb! and some passages are truly breath-taking. Yes, Thomas Wolfe sometimes comes across as a pretentious writer. Yes, the main character of Eugene Gant sometimes comes across as a painfully smug, annoying and downright brattish lout throughout parts of the book but honestly speaking, think about it! Didn’t we all go through that phase at some stage in our life? If you think you sometime ‘escaped’ this phase or ‘stepped around’ it, then you are fooling nobody but yourself.<br /><br /><br />This is a great coming-of-age novel in which Wolfe recalls, through a thinly disguised fictionalized account of his own upbringing, the slings and arrows of growing up. Growing pains. The descriptions of Asheville, where Wolfe grew up, his family home, Dixieland, and many of his forays into various places over the countryside were a real delight to read about. Wolfe’s words carry a certain power too – they put me right there in the middle of the action. I felt like I could have been standing right next to him.<br /><br />As is the case with most people who read this book, my favourite character was Ben and I don’t want to give anything away to people who have not read the book yet so will just say that I felt sorry for how he was neglected by the others (the ‘silent fight through life of the silent one of the family’ – I suspect he was only ‘silent’ because none of his self-centered family, with the possible exception of Eugene, even tried to take the time to understand him!) and also the last 100 pages of the book were so powerful that it moved me to tears. However, my FAVOURITE part of the book (which I re-read about five times) was when Eugene took out his anger on Ben when Eugene was pining after his first love (who it turns out was a young harlot who was actually engaged to someone else and left poor young Eugene lying in the lurch) and Ben told him to forget her and ‘to hell with all of them’ anyway. I’m sure many of us can relate to similar moments in our own lives, such as the first painful break-up we had, the first heartbreak or other times when we have been mad at family, friends or when the world leaves us cold. <br /><br />What I particularly loved about this book is how it illustrates how humans set out young, innocent and eager to explore life only to become increasingly disappointed when it doesn’t turn out the way we expected it to be. This happens to Eugene as he notices that the real world is vastly different from the utopian and phantastic pictures he has in his head from all the books he read in his youth. Also, sometimes life does not offer ANY solutions to our problems. Life is an eternal mystery and we discover that as we get older. Why are we here? Where do we come from? What does it all mean? Who were we at that particular time in our lives? And the recurring Wolfean answer is, “O lost!”. The answers are blowing in the wind. We all came into exile and we are all lost stumbling around in the dark for answers. These are the main underlying themes of the book. <br /><br />Apart from Ben, I thought most of the characters in the book were pretty dreadful really. The father is a pathetic drunk most of the time. The mother is a stingy woman who seems more interested in saving a buck and trying her hand in the local real estate market than her actual family. Luke is alright but not really given much attention in the book. Helen is the fiery daughter (there’s one in every family), who despite her courage and strength, I found as annoying as the father she adores and she inherits the same flaws as her father. As I have already mentioned, Eugene, the protagonist, based on Wolfe himself we can assume, is a spoilt, brattish young fool but through the changes and anguish he goes through we somehow come to sympathize with him anyway as some part of our own youth reawakens and remembers the bumpy, joyful, confusing and terrifying ride that it sometimes was.<br /><br />I should have read this when I was much younger – before I went out in the world myself. It might have taught me a few things before I found out the hard way, like Eugene. But, alas, I guess the beautiful innocence in all of us must die sooner or later and that is one of the many things that are ‘lost’. <br /><br />In summary, I highly recommend this book. They don’t make writers like Wolfe anymore. Fans of Kerouac (like myself) and Phillip Roth will probably also enjoy this book by Wolfe who was idolized by both of these well-known authors. Without Wolfe, there would have been no The Town and the City (Kerouac) or American Pastoral (Roth). Five Stars!!!<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="10167955415005540219" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


