    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_972974301" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/972974301" />
    <a title="Eric" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3170906-eric"><img alt="Eric" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1263902845p2/3170906.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/972974301?book_show_action=true">Jun 20, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Eric" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Eric" href="/user/show/3170906-eric">Eric</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer972974301" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17228976588610638563">The quintessential American autobiographical coming-of-age novel.<br/><br/>Thomas Wolfe was born in 1900. So was his fictional surrogate, Eugene Gant. Wolfe grew up in Asheville, North Carolina, a city nestled in a basin of mountains. Asheville was something of a resort community for southerners who wanted to get some mountain air without leaving the South. A lot of people were afflicted with tuberculosis back then, and the recommended cure was to spend a few weeks or months at a sanitarium and breathe th</span>
  <span id="freeText17228976588610638563" style="display:none">The quintessential American autobiographical coming-of-age novel.<br /><br />Thomas Wolfe was born in 1900. So was his fictional surrogate, Eugene Gant. Wolfe grew up in Asheville, North Carolina, a city nestled in a basin of mountains. Asheville was something of a resort community for southerners who wanted to get some mountain air without leaving the South. A lot of people were afflicted with tuberculosis back then, and the recommended cure was to spend a few weeks or months at a sanitarium and breathe the cool, dry air. Asheville is represented in this novel by Altamont.<br /><br />Altamont is neither part of the South nor of the North. Its cool elevation sets it apart from the South, and its Confederate heritage separates it from Yankee territory.<br /><br />Eugene's family includes his father, W.O. Gant, a stonecutter, subject to drunken rages and faux-Shakespearean monologues listing his life's complaints. Eugene's mother is Eliza, a grasping, wheeler-dealer businesswoman who buys and sells real estate and runs a boarding house. Eugene's siblings are a rowdy crew that include ne'er-do-well Steve, good-natured huckster Luke, quiet Ben, and work-weary but high-humored Helen. Eugene is, of course, the tortured writer. The apple who seems to have fallen far from the tree.<br /><br />The story starts in an elevated, high-poetic fashion that comes and goes, alternating with more straightforward prose peppered with earthy humor. I told someone recently to stick with the book during the most high-flown poetic passages, because Wolfe can go from Walt Whitman to John Steinbeck on a dime.<br /><br />When you read this book, be prepared for racist and/or anti-semitic passages, which are scattered throughout the book. I don't know a lot about Wolfe's adult personality to be able to tell you whether the views expressed are those of the adult writer, or merely an expression of the attitudes he grew up with, and for a time accepted. One thing is for sure: the culture in which Eugene Gant was raised saw no great stigma against the practice of young white boys seeking out sexual experiences in the black section of town.<br /><br />Racism aside, one thing this book (and other books, such as The Adventures of Tom Sawyer) illustrates, is that the essential trappings of American childhood hadn't changed a lot in the intervening years until I grew up in the 60s and 70s. I can still relate. A lot of the slang remains intact (such as "S.O.L."), as does the practice of the older generation saying they used to have to walk twelve miles to school in eight feet of snow. Dime novels were replaced by pulp magazines, which were replaced by comic books, but there was always printed fodder out there to stimulate a kid's imagination.<br /><br />Eugene comes off as self-absorbed, pretentious, and self-pitying at times, but isn't that how most adolescent kids are? Especially bright outsiders that don't fit into society's mainstream.<br /><br />I'm going to Asheville this summer and am going to visit the boarding house that was the basis for Eliza Gant's "Dixieland" in the novel. Can't wait to see it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17228976588610638563" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


